  <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">YAK</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">10 pts</span></span>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">K Tile Strategy</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Don't hoard K:</span> With only 1 tile in the bag, your opponent knows you have it if they track tiles. Play K within 2 turns of drawing it to maintain rack flexibility and avoid predictability.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Target DLS with K:</span> K on a double-letter square = 10 points from one tile. That's more than most entire 3-letter words. Prioritise DLS placement whenever K is in your rack.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">CK endings are gold:</span> BACK, DECK, KICK, LOCK, TUCK — CK ending words are everywhere and score well. If an existing word ends near a premium square, adding CK can create huge parallel plays.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">K Combo Patterns Worth Memorising</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">K appears in <span class="text-white font-medium">three dominant patterns</span>: CK endings (BACK, DECK, KICK), KN beginnings (KNACK, KNIFE, KNOT), and NK middles (THINK, DRINK, BLANK). Each unlocks dozens of valid words.</p>
</div>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">-CK Endings (most common)</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">BACK, DECK, FLICK, KNOCK, QUICK, STACK, TRICK, WHACK — adds K(5)+C(3) = 8 points to roots</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <p class="text-blue-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">KN- Beginnings</p>
